2026-04-16 12:14:26 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['main load lamp (primary lamp in load module)'] hypothesis_explanation='The supply module delivers correct 12 V (green LED on), polarity is correct into and out of the control module (verified by cable‑polarity tests and the red ‘inverted cables’ LED remaining off), and +12 V appears correctly at the load module input when the switch is closed. Measurements inside the load module show that the series diode is good (since ≈11.2 V is present after it) and that both lamps see the full supply voltage. The internal indicator lamp has normal continuity (~500 Ω), but the main load lamp measures open circuit (~1 GΩ vs 120 Ω nominal) while the full supply voltage appears across it. This means the main lamp filament is broken and no current flows through it, so it will never light even though the rest of the circuit is functioning. Therefore the root cause is a failed/open‑filament main load lamp in the load module.'
